            	<a href="http://www.nbcnews.com/id/31066137/media-kit/" target="_blank">advertisement</a>
            </div>
            <div class="ad-content ad-xs boxflex" data-placement="boxflex"></div>
            </div>
            <div class="article_col-main article_col-main-left article_main">
              <div class="article-body" itemprop="articleBody">
                    <p> A batch of letters written by the late novelist Harper Lee to various friends over the years fetched more than $33,500 at auction Thursday night — including snarky snail mail blasting a hotel bearing Donald Trump's name. </p>
                
              
              
              
                    <p> The celebrated &quot;To Kill a Mockingbird&quot; author, who <a href="http://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/harper-lee-author-kill-mockingbird-dead-89-n521646">died Feb. 19</a> at age 89, knocked the Trump Taj Mahal in Atlantic City, New Jersey, in an August 1990 missive to friend Doris Leapard. </p>
                
              
              
              
                  <figure class="img_full">
                    <noscript><img class="img-responsive img_inline" src="http://media2.s-nbcnews.com/j/newscms/2016_13/1480476/harper-lee-ejo-040116_e9ba75f88942c40a45b1fc49d1760b05.nbcnews-fp-360-360.jpg" alt="Image: LIFESTYLE-US-VOTE-LITERATURE" title="Image: LIFESTYLE-US-VOTE-LITERATURE" itemprop="image"/></noscript>
                    <a href="http://media2.s-nbcnews.com/j/newscms/2016_13/1480476/harper-lee-ejo-040116_e9ba75f88942c40a45b1fc49d1760b05.nbcnews-ux-2880-1000.jpg" class="js-lightbox lightbox_link">
                      <button class="btn btn_overlay"><i class="fa fa-expand"></i></button>
                      <img class="js-lazy img-responsive img_inline" src="//sslnodeassets.nbcnews.com/images/transparent-placeholder.gif" data-original="http://media2.s-nbcnews.com/j/newscms/2016_13/1480476/harper-lee-ejo-040116_e9ba75f88942c40a45b1fc49d1760b05.nbcnews-ux-600-480.jpg" alt="Image: LIFESTYLE-US-VOTE-LITERATURE" title="Image: LIFESTYLE-US-VOTE-LITERATURE"/>
                    </a>
                    <div class="js-caption_wrapper">
                      <figcaption class="img-caption img-caption_default no-margin-bottom"><span class="img-caption_txt">Some of the 29 personal correspondences by author Harper Lee are displayed in Los Angeles on March 28, 2016.</span> <i class="fa fa-camera" aria-hidden="true"></i>ROBYN BECK / AFP - Getty Images</figcaption>
                    </div>
                  </figure>
                
              
              
              
                    <p> Lee tells Leapard she can't think of a worst place to spend eternity than the garish gaming palace that had opened a few months earlier at a cost of nearly $1 billion. </p>
                
              
              
              
                    <p> <strong>Related: <a href="http://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/change-org-petition-asks-university-alabama-rename-building-harper-lee-n523556">Change.org Petition Asks University of Alabama to Rename Building For Harper Lee</a></strong> </p>
                
              
                    <div class="ad-container ad-container_default ad-container_mobile ad-hide">
                      <div class="ad-label ad-hide">
                      	<a href="http://www.nbcnews.com/id/31066137/media-kit/" target="_blank">advertisement</a>
                      </div>
                      <div class="ad-content ad-xs box1" data-placement="box1"></div>
                    </div>
              
              
                    <p> &quot;The worst punishment God can devise for this sinner is to make her spirit reside eternally at the Trump Taj Mahal in Atlantic City,&quot; she wrote in the letter, which sold for $3,926, according to Nate D. Sanders Auctions in Los Angeles. </p>
                
              
              
              
                  <figure class="img_full">
                    <noscript><img class="img-responsive img_inline" src="http://media1.s-nbcnews.com/j/newscms/2016_13/1480481/trump-taj-mahal-ejo-040116_4dc535eb3ba5628dda0ed68a1e27956c.nbcnews-fp-360-360.jpg" alt="Image: Donald Trump" title="Image: Donald Trump" itemprop="image"/></noscript>
                    <a href="http://media1.s-nbcnews.com/j/newscms/2016_13/1480481/trump-taj-mahal-ejo-040116_4dc535eb3ba5628dda0ed68a1e27956c.nbcnews-ux-2880-1000.jpg" class="js-lightbox lightbox_link">
                      <button class="btn btn_overlay"><i class="fa fa-expand"></i></button>
                      <img class="js-lazy img-responsive img_inline" src="//sslnodeassets.nbcnews.com/images/transparent-placeholder.gif" data-original="http://media1.s-nbcnews.com/j/newscms/2016_13/1480481/trump-taj-mahal-ejo-040116_4dc535eb3ba5628dda0ed68a1e27956c.nbcnews-ux-600-480.jpg" alt="Image: Donald Trump" title="Image: Donald Trump"/>
                    </a>
                    <div class="js-caption_wrapper">
                      <figcaption class="img-caption img-caption_default no-margin-bottom"><span class="img-caption_txt">In this April 5, 1990, file photo, Donald Trump stands next to a genie lamp as the lights of his Trump Taj Mahal Casino Resort light up the evening sky marking the grand opening of the venture in Atlantic City, N.J.</span> <i class="fa fa-camera" aria-hidden="true"></i>Mike Derer / AP</figcaption>
                    </div>
                  </figure>
                
              
              
              
                    <p> It's unclear why Lee decided to rip into the Trump Taj Mahal, which the now-GOP presidential candidate trumpeted at the time as a boon for Atlantic City — a down-on-its-luck gambling mecca. </p>
                
              
              
              
                    <p> &quot;It's just what Atlantic City needs,&quot; Trump <a href="http://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/news/harper-lee-called-trump-taj-mahal-worst-punishment-god-can/article_4b4124e8-f50c-11e5-b2a6-bfd5ca190e3f.html?mode=story">told The Press of Atlantic City</a> the year it opened. </p>
                
              
              
              
                    <p> While Trump's name is still on the casino, it is currently owned by billionaire investor Carl Icahn, who purchased it in bankruptcy court in February. Trump also<a href="http://www.cnbc.com/2016/03/23/the-associated-press-icahn-taj-future-at-risk-amid-benefits-expansion-talks.html"> no longer owns or controls</a> the casino company — Trump Entertainment Resorts — he founded. </p>
                
              
                    <div class="ad-container ad-container_default ad-container_mobile ad-hide">
                      <div class="ad-label ad-hide">
                      	<a href="http://www.nbcnews.com/id/31066137/media-kit/" target="_blank">advertisement</a>
                      </div>
                      <div class="ad-content ad-xs box2" data-placement="box2"></div>
                    </div>
              
              
                    <p> Bidding for Lee's sardonic take on the Trump casino began at $750; it ultimately attracted 11 bids. </p>
                
              
              
              
                
              
              
              
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
